{"cursor":"4850","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Mathurin Jacques Brisson' (30 April 1723 – 23 June 1806) was a French\nzoologist and natural philosopher.\n\nBrisson was born at Fontenay-le-Comte. The earlier part of his life was spent in\nthe pursuit of natural history, his published works in this field included Le\nRÃ¨gne animal (1756) [http://books.google.com/books/about/Le_Regne_Animal_D-\nivise_En_IX_Classes.html?id=fVlESwAACAAJ Google Books] La Regne Animal.\nand the highly-regarded Ornithologie\n(1760). [http://archive.org/details/ornithologieoumt02bris Biodiversity\nHeritage Library] Ornithologie, etc.\n\nAs a young man, he was a disciple and assistant of R. A. F. Reaumur. For a\nperiod of time he was an instructor of physical sciences and natural history to\nthe family of the monarch. [http://books.google.com/books?id=_4AXAAAAYAAJ&p-\ng=PA139&lpg=PA139&dq=%22Mathurin+Jacques+Brisson%22+1723&source=bl&ots=9AL19x_u-\nZj&sig=dDWRVfa2dtDgYQk413lSyg0qRmQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lZjLUYzSDqrfiALT6YB4&ved=0CCsQ-\n6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=%22Mathurin%20Jacques%20Brisson%22%201723&f=false\nTaxidermy: Bibliography and Biography] by William Swainson He held the\nchair of physics at the College of Navarre, and from 1759 was a member of the\nAcademy of Sciences.\n\nA significant work involving the \"specific weight of bodies\" was his Pesanteur\nSpÃ©cifique des Corps (1787). [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k94851w\nGallica] Pesanteur SpÃ©cifique des Corps. In his investigations of\nelectricity, Brisson was opposed to the theories of Priestley and Franklin. [http://books.google.com/books?id=uJtlAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-\nPA963&lpg=RA1-\nPA963&dq=%22Brisson,+Mathurin%22+%22+Fontenay+le+Comte%22&source=bl&ots=TRunORP-\nGhc&sig=0Gl9Tz1761OWCi5aibla59t7gS8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lZrLUc6oOsSSiALStYH4Bw&ved=0C-\nEcQ6AEwBzgK#v=onepage&q=%22Brisson%2C%20Mathurin%22%20%22%20Fontenay%20le%20Com-\nte%22&f=false The English CyclopÃ¦dia: A New Dictionary of Universal Knowledge\n..., Volum